Priority — nice and renice.

The Linux scheduler hands out CPU time among all the runnable processes, and by default everyone gets a fair share. But you can tilt the scales, and the way you do it is with a value called nice.

Here's the range, and it's genuinely confusing at first: nice runs from minus-twenty, which is the highest priority, to positive-nineteen, which is the lowest. The default is zero. So it's backwards from what you'd expect: a higher nice number means lower priority. The trick to remembering it is to think about politeness. Nice means "how willing am I to yield the CPU to others." A process at nice nineteen is very nice, very willing to step aside. A process at nice minus-twenty is selfish; it grabs the CPU and doesn't yield.

There's an important permission rule. Only root can decrease a nice value, that is, raise a process's priority. Any regular user can increase nice, lowering the priority of their own processes. That asymmetry exists so that users can't just hand themselves more CPU than they're entitled to.

To start a command with a particular nice value, you use nice dash-n and the number. So nice dash-n ten, then the command, launches it at nice ten, lower priority. To change the priority of a process that's already running, you use renice. renice five dash-p and a PID sets that process to nice five. And renice ten dash-u alice renices every one of alice's processes at once.

There's a sibling command worth knowing too: ionice, which controls input-output priority, completely separate from CPU priority. Its class three is "idle," meaning "only touch the disk when nothing else needs it." The classic combination is for a heavy backup you don't want to choke your production workload: nice dash-n nineteen, ionice dash-c three, then rsync. That runs the copy at the lowest CPU priority and idle disk priority, so it politely gets out of everyone's way. For exam-level work, know nice and renice cold, and treat ionice as a useful bonus.
